I've heard (don't know if it's true) that they even sleep in shifts, sharing beds. We get a lot of ladies from Jamaica on housekeeping at the hotels. They used to live within walking distance, now they're bused out as far as one could get in the next town over (which blends into our city lines, so only locals know where one ends and the other begins), and they're at a Red Roof Inn motel.\nWith apartment rentals, landlords will rent to students during the academic year, then jack the monthly rent up in the summer months, to thousands a month, to get tourists. Office workers from the tri-state area will pool their resources and divvy up the weekends amongst themselves. Or they're AirBnB.\nWe're beginning to organize and demand that city council at least force AirBnB owners to register. But yes, a moratorium would help.  \nI had not been living in this house even 24 hours before I received something in my mailbox that said a young man who buys property and flips them or rents them out was interested in my house. A couple of months later, I received a phone call while I was on a zoom meeting with someone, and glanced at the caller ID. I'm pretty certain it was his father calling. The old guy down the street thinks that they are interested in his house because he put a jacuzzi in the basement and he has a great waterview. I'm pretty sure they want his house, my house, and the one in between it, to knock them all down and put up something grandiose with water view that does not fit in with the rest of the houses on this street.",

          "snippet": {
            "channelId": "UCJ0uqCI0Vqr2Rrt1HseGirg",
            "videoId": "mGtV1cdj0qg",
            "textDisplay": "James states the cladding used on Grenfell “Actually met building codes at the time”. This is completely untrue. The public inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire has found that external cladding did not meet Building Regulations at the time on installation. Sir Martin Moore-Bick’s conclusion on cladding contained in report on Phase 1 of the public inquiry into the fire at Grenfell Tower concluded that the cladding did not comply with the Building Regulations aimed at preventing the external spread of firebut instead ‘actively promoted it’.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBick said: ‘There was compelling evidence that the external walls of the building failed to comply with Requirement B4(1) of Schedule 1 to the Building Regulations 2010, in that they did not adequately resist the spread of fire having regard to the height, use and position of the building.’\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIn the report, Bick signposted the likely focus of Phase 2 of the public inquiry.             "textOriginal": "I am also a poet. Of course, I'm not worthy to even be compared to the great Amanda Gorman. Eighty-Four.\nIt was at a summer session because I had failed English 101 two years before.\nA failure due more to my citizenship in a different realm than to the failings of my intellect, aptitude, or the magnanimity of my core.\n“You have such a poignant and evocative writing style,” wrote my teacher on the short story I had submitted the week before.\nI had written about a lonely sojourn on a desolate beach in the pregnant moment,\nWhen sunset injures day's abandon and grants night the freedom to roam.\nI had written about the mighty North Shore mountains,\nHoary with age and reverberating with an energy ineffable to the mind,\nBut savored by the soul.\nI remembered how exhausting of mindbut above all of the soul, writing that short-story had been.\nI tried to reveal my spirit bare and exposed.\nI tried to destroy the ramparts and blow open the heavy gates shielding my secretive core.\nBut through my exhausting efforts, I had only succeeded in weakening the facade between me and the world,\nUsually held at arm's length,\nBut through my story then, only slightly nearer yet still remote.\nThere is an essence within everyone hidden in a chamber far beneath the veneer that encrusts our core.\nWe seldom allow it expression beyond just its fractured shadows dancing on an external wall.\nBut if we all dig deep and reach into this secretive chamber,\nWe will, to our astonishment, discover we are all reaching into the same chamber,\nNot a separate one for each within the all.\nAnd then we will grasp each other's same-hand.\nWe all share the same soul.\nI knew that in the novel of my compulsion I would have to expose this chamber,\nRamparts and heavy gates destroyed once and for all.\nAnd my novel would then cry out from this collective chamber,\nAnd speak for my left and for my right with one voice for all.\nIt would be the ineffable ground of being reaching out to humanity from the navel of Creation,\nProclaiming the dawn of a Third Age.\nIt would announce the sunset of the Second Age before this coming dawn.\nA moment pregnant with change that will forever be remembered in the annals of the Civilization of Man.\nIt would herald a paradigm shift far greater than the Renaissance,\nNot just an age of reasonbut of reason and divinity intertwined as an inseparable whole.\nI envision the Third Age to be promoting the two primordial dancers,\nThe abstract magical, and the other, its complementary whole.\nTo engage in the Dance and thence unshard into the Eternal Garden from whence we all came forth.\nThey are in Eternity entwined but sharded into the realms of space and time.\nThey are shards of the divine.\nWould composing such a novel be an arduous journey,\nExhausting my body and above all my core?\nWould I be as a drowning man,\nGasping for breath,\nKicking and screaming while with futility grasping for shore?\nBut would every paragraph and page exhaust me,\nYet also leave me yearning for more?\nIt would, I am sure.\nThis arduous compulsion will also uplift and invigorate me with waves of catharsis and frisson.\nAnd I pray dearly for the same in my reader,\nof soul-piercing joy.\nIf I fail to evoke the same in my audience then I would have failed to breach the ramparts and the gates shielding my innermost chamber,\nOur collective soul.\nOnly within this innermost shared sanctum can I truly touch someone's soul.\nAnd by         "topLevelComment": {
          "kind": "youtube#comment",
          "etag": "LreWEoyYb7ryE27nhn_2ekLhWn8",
          "id": "Ugzwd-ZBPsY29bIvHuF4AaABAg",
          "snippet": {
            "channelId": "UCCj956IF62FbT7Gouszaj9w",
            "videoId": "W1fiijqrKuc",
            "textDisplay": "Watching this on BBC i-Player at the moment.\u003cbr\u003e...and it is really VERY good! 🤔\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSet in 1814 London, it really captures the seedy, fog-infested atmosphere, of those dangerous times.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLots of scenes set on the Thames foreshore, so it feels very "close" to me, as someone who has spent a lot of time on the banks of the Thames over the years, and who's family worked on the river, and lived right on the banks for many generations.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTom Hardy is excellent as a troubled son returning from Africa to inherit a small piece of land on the yet-to-be-drawn Canadian/U.S border, the ownership of which, is the desire of both the all-powerful East India Company...AND the fledgling United States of America, because it holds the key to trade-routes to China.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJonathan Pryce plays an excellent "baddie" as top dog at the East India Company, and Stephen Graham plays a nicely-untrustworthy "fixer".\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI can highly recommend this show, if you enjoy well-written, and acted, Regency-period drama, with a definitely different-slant to the usual meek Jane Austin fare of the same period.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePride and Prejudice...it ISN'T! 🤣🤔",
            "textOriginal": "Watching this on BBC i-Player at the moment.\n...and it is really VERY good! 🤔\n\nSet in 1814 London, it really captures the seedy, fog-infested atmosphere, of those dangerous times.\n\nLots of scenes set on the Thames foreshore, so it feels very \"close\" to me, as someone who has spent a lot of time on the banks of the Thames over the years, and who's family worked on the river, and lived right on the banks for many generations.\n\nTom Hardy is excellent as a troubled son returning from Africa to inherit a small piece of land on the yet-to-be-drawn Canadian/U.S border, the ownership of which, is the desire of both the all-powerful East India Company...AND the fledgling United States of America, because it holds the key to trade-routes to China.\n\nJonathan Pryce plays an excellent \"baddie\" as top dog at the East India Company, and Stephen Graham plays a nicely-untrustworthy \"fixer\".\n\nI can highly recommend this show, if you enjoy well-written, and acted, Regency-period drama, with a definitely different-slant to the usual meek Jane Austin fare of the same period.\n\nPride and Prejudice...it ISN'T! 🤣🤔",
            "authorDisplayName": "Christo Guichard",
